    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq"><summary>What are the dental options for self-employed people?<span class="ic">+</span></summary><div class="ans">The main options are an individual dental insurance policy or a dental savings plan. Insurance pays a share but has premiums, waiting periods, and an annual cap. A savings plan is a lower-cost membership that discounts care immediately with no cap, and you can use both together.</div></details>
      <details class="faq"><summary>Is a dental savings plan good for freelancers?<span class="ic">+</span></summary><div class="ans">It fits many freelancers well, because it is inexpensive, works immediately, requires no employer, and can be canceled or stacked as your situation changes. The tradeoff is that it discounts care rather than paying for it.</div></details>
      <details class="faq"><summary>How much does a self-employed dental savings plan cost?<span class="ic">+</span></summary><div class="ans">Individual memberships commonly cost $100 to $200 a year, often far less than an individual insurance premium. Prices vary by plan and seller, so confirm the current price at checkout.</div></details>
      <details class="faq"><summary>Can I switch to insurance later?<span class="ic">+</span></summary><div class="ans">Yes. Dental coverage has no medical underwriting, so you can add an individual PPO whenever it makes sense, and even keep the savings plan alongside it to keep discounting once you hit the annual maximum.</div></details>
